Pages = {519-535},
Month = {DEC},
Abstract = {Self-incompatibility (SI) is defined as the inability to produce zygotes
   after self-pollination in a fertile hermaphrodite plant, which has
   stamens and pistils in the same flower. This structural organization of
   the hermaphrodite flower increases the risk of self-pollination, leading
   to low genetic diversity. To avoid this problem plants have established
   several pollination systems, among which the most elegant system is
   surely SI. The SI trait can be observed in Brassica crops, including
   cabbage, broccoli, turnip and radish. To produce hybrid seed of these
   crops efficiently, the SI trait has been employed in an agricultural
   context. From another point of view, the recognition reaction of SI
   during pollen-stigma interaction is an excellent model system for
   cell-cell communication and signal transduction in higher plants. In
   this review, we describe the molecular mechanisms of SI in Brassicaceae,
   which have been dissected by genetic, physiological, and biological
   approaches, and we discuss the future prospects in relation to
   associated scientific fields and new technologies.},
